To modify the given method to use the graph equivalent and handle circular dependencies without causing StackOverFlowError or LazyInitializationException, you can make use of the entity graph functionality provided by JPA. Here's the modified code:

```java
public <T> List<T> loadAllData(Class<T> type) {
    Transaction tx = null;

    try (Session session = HibernateUtil.getSessionFactory().openSession()) {
        tx = session.beginTransaction();

        CriteriaBuilder builder = session.getCriteriaBuilder();
        CriteriaQuery<T> criteria = builder.createQuery(type);
        Root<T> root = criteria.from(type);

        EntityGraph<T> graph = session.createEntityGraph(type);
        graph.addAttributeNodes("yourAssociations"); // Replace "yourAssociations" with the actual associations you want to fetch eagerly

        FetchGraph<T> fetchGraph = session.getEntityGraph(type.getName() + ".fetchGraph");
        criteria.setHint("javax.persistence.fetchgraph", fetchGraph);

        criteria.select(root);

        List<T> data = session.createQuery(criteria).getResultList();

        tx.commit();

        return data;
    }
}
```

In the modified code, an EntityGraph is created for the given entity type and the desired associations are added to it using the addAttributeNodes() method. This ensures that the specified associations are fetched eagerly along with the main entity when executing the query.

A FetchGraph is also created using the entity graph and set as a hint using the setHint() method. This tells the JPA provider (such as Hibernate) to use the defined fetch graph for the query.

By using the entity graph and fetch graph, circular dependencies and lazy initialization exceptions can be handled properly, as the associations specified in the graph will be eagerly fetched, avoiding any lazy initialization issues.

Note: You should replace "yourAssociations" with the actual associations you want to fetch eagerly in the graph.

Yes, "yourAssociations" refers to the name of the field or attribute in the entity class that represents the association that you want to fetch eagerly. The field name should match the actual name of the association field defined in your entity class. For example, if you have a Book entity with an association field named "authors" of type List<Author>, "yourAssociations" should be replaced with "authors".

Here's an example:

```java
EntityGraph<Book> graph = session.createEntityGraph(Book.class);
graph.addAttributeNodes("authors"); // Replace "authors" with the actual name of your association field

FetchGraph<Book> fetchGraph = session.getEntityGraph(Book.class.getName() + ".fetchGraph");
criteria.setHint("javax.persistence.fetchgraph", fetchGraph);
```

This code creates an entity graph for the Book entity, adds the "authors" association to the graph using the addAttributeNodes() method, and sets the graph as a fetch graph hint in the criteria query.

