```java
public <T> List<T> loadAllData(Class<T> type, String association) {
    Transaction tx = null;

    try (Session session = HibernateUtil.getSessionFactory().openSession()) {
        tx = session.beginTransaction();

        CriteriaBuilder builder = session.getCriteriaBuilder();
        CriteriaQuery<T> criteria = builder.createQuery(type);
        Root<T> root = criteria.from(type);

        EntityGraph<T> graph = session.createEntityGraph(type);

        if (!association.isEmpty()) {
            graph.addAttributeNodes(association);
        }

        FetchGraph<T> fetchGraph = session.getEntityGraph(type.getName() + ".fetchGraph");
        criteria.setHint("javax.persistence.fetchgraph", fetchGraph);

        criteria.select(root);

        List<T> data = session.createQuery(criteria).getResultList();

        tx.commit();

        return data;
    }
}
```

With this modified code, you can specify the association/field name as a parameter when calling the `loadAllData()` method. If the provided association name is not empty, it will be added to the entity graph using `graph.addAttributeNodes()`. If it is empty, no associations will be added to the graph, and the data will be loaded without eagerly fetching any associations.

For example, you can call the method as follows:

```java
List<Book> booksWithAuthors = loadAllData(Book.class, "authors"); // Eagerly fetch the "authors" association

List<Book> allBooks = loadAllData(Book.class, ""); // Load all books without eagerly fetching any associations
```

Note that it's important to ensure that the association name you provide as an argument matches the actual association field name in your entity class.

